  1. Make a histogram of the total number of steps taken each day
df %>% 
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarise(total_steps = sum(steps, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  pull(total_steps) %>% 
  hist(x = ., main = 'Total number of step taken each day', xlab = 'Total number of steps')

  1. Calculate and report the mean and median of the total number of steps taken per day
df %>% 
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_steps   = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_steps = median(steps, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -date, names_to = 'variable', values_to = 'values') %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = date, y = values, color = variable)) +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, ncol = 2, scales = 'free_y') +
  geom_line(size = 1, show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(x = 'Steps', y = 'Date') +
  theme_minimal()

What is the average daily activity pattern?

  1. Make a time series plot of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all days (y-axis)
df %>% 
  group_by(interval) %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_steps   = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = interval, y = mean_steps)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  labs(x = 'Interval', y = 'Steps') +
  theme_minimal()

  1. Which 5-minute interval, on average across all the days in the dataset, contains the maximum number of steps?
df %>% 
  group_by(interval) %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_steps   = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>% 
  slice_max(n = 1, order_by = mean_steps)

Imputing missing values

  1. Calculate and report the total number of missing values in the dataset
df %>% 
  is.na() %>% 
  colSums
##    steps     date interval 
##     2304        0        0
  1. Devise a strategy for filling in all of the missing values in the dataset
df %>% 
  group_by(interval) %>% 
  mutate(steps = ifelse(test = is.na(steps), 
                        yes = round(x = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE), digits = 0), no = steps))

  1. Create a new dataset that is equal to the original dataset but with the missing data filled in
df_imputed <- df %>% 
  group_by(interval) %>% 
  mutate(steps = ifelse(test = is.na(steps), 
                        yes = round(x = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE), digits = 0), no = steps)) %>% 
  ungroup

  1. What is the impact of imputing missing data on the estimates of the total daily number of steps?

Data became more normally distributed, with much more observations towards 10K to 15K steps.

Are there differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends?

  1. Create a new factor variable in the dataset with two levels – “weekday” and “weekend” indicating whether a given date is a weekday or weekend day
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(
    wweek = weekdays(date),
    wweek = case_when(wweek %in% c('Saturday', 'Sunday') ~ 'weekend',
                      TRUE ~ 'weekday')
  )
df

  1. Make a panel plot containing a time series plot of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all weekday days or weekend days (y-axis).
df %>% 
  group_by(interval, wweek) %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_steps = mean(steps, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = 'drop'
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = interval, y = mean_steps, color = wweek)) +
  facet_wrap(~ wweek, ncol = 2, scales = 'free') +
  geom_line(size = 1, show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(x = 'Interval', y = 'Steps') +
  theme_minimal()
